max_ops: maximum number of operators Enumerate the number of possible unary-binary trees that can be generated from empty nodes. D[e][n] represents the number of different binary trees with n nodes that can be generated from e empty nodes, using the following recursion:

\(p_1\) = if binary trees, 1 if unary binary

generate_excitation(rng: RandomState, n_inputs_points: int, input_dimension: int = 1, normalize: bool | None = False) → ndarray[source]#

Generate excitation time series data with different sampling strategies.

This method primarily calls our highly encapsulated Excitation class to generate sampled time series data X. This sampled time series is then input into the constructed complex system (symbolic expression) to further generate a response time series.

Parameters:

  • rng The random number generator in NumPy with fixed seed.

  • n_inputs_points The number of points of time series to generate.

  • input_dimension The number of dimensions of time series to generate.

  • normalize If True, normalize the output time series.

Returns:

The generated excitation time series.

generate_leaf(rng: RandomState, input_dimension: int) → str[source]#

Generate a leaf node in the sampling expression.

The logic behind this code generation process first determines whether to generate a random number. If no random number is generated, leaf node variables are generated. If all leaf node variables have been traversed and there are still leaf nodes remaining, integer nodes or random leaf nodes are generated based on the specified probability.

Parameters:

  • rng The random number generator in NumPy with fixed seed.

  • input_dimension The dimension of the symbolic expression.

Returns:

The leaf node, rand, x_{dimension} or int.

generate_ops(rng: RandomState, arity: int) → str[source]#

Select a specific operation for an operator node

generate_symbolic_expression(rng: RandomState, input_dimension: int | None = None, output_dimension: int | None = None, nb_unary_ops: int | None = None, nb_binary_ops: int | None = None, return_all: bool = False)[source]#

Generates a multivariate set of symbolic expressions with channel dependencies based on input parameters and a random number generator.

Specific steps for generating a tree: (1) Determine hyperparameters: First, determine the relevant hyperparameters. If the user specifies them, use the user-input parameters; otherwise, randomly generate the parameters. (2) Generate the trunk of the binary tree: Use binary operators to form the basic structure of the symbolic expression and add leaf nodes of random numbers and variables. (3) Add unary operators: Randomly insert unary operators into the constructed binary tree data to enrich its operations. (4) Final improvement: Add other variables or perform radial transformations to further improve its diversity.

Parameters:

  • rng The random number generator in NumPy with fixed seed.

  • input_dimension Number of input dimensions in the target symbolic expression to be generated.

  • output_dimension Number of output dimensions in the generated symbolic expression to be generated.

  • nb_unary_ops Number of binary operators used in a binary expression.

  • nb_binary_ops Number of binary operators used in a binary expression.

  • return_all Whether to return all information in the generation of the trees.

Returns:

The generated trees (symbolic expression or complex system).

generate_tree(rng: RandomState, nb_binary_ops: int, input_dimension: int) → Node[source]#

get_rid(x: ndarray, y: ndarray) → Tuple[ndarray, ndarray][source]#

Remove illegal values from the generated time series from the complex system.

To ensure accurate sampling of complex systems, we discard values outside the domain of the symbolic expression $f(cdot)$ or values that are too large. While this may reduce the sampling efficiency of data generation, it will improve the quality of data generation to a certain extent.

Parameters:

  • x The original excitation sampling time series.

  • y The generated time series from the complex system.

Returns:

The input and output time series which removed the illegal values.

run(rng: RandomState, n_inputs_points: int, input_dimension: int = 1, output_dimension: int = 1, max_trials: int | None = None, input_normalize: str | None = 'z-score', output_normalize: bool | None = 'z-score', input_max_scale: float | None = 16.0, output_max_scale: float | None = 16.0, offset: Tuple[float, float] | None = None, save_path: str | None = None) → Tuple[None, None, None] | Tuple[NodeList, ndarray, ndarray][source]#

Generate the symbolic expression (complex system) and the excitation time series.

Parameters:

  • rng The random number generator in NumPy with fixed seed.

  • n_inputs_points The number of points of time series to generate.

  • input_dimension The number of the input dimensions of time series to generate.

  • output_dimension The number of the output dimensions of time series or symbol expression to generate.

  • max_trials The maximum number of trials to generate and try.

  • input_normalize Normalize the input time series, choice of z-score or max-min or None, defaults to z-score.

  • output_normalize Normalize the output time series, choice of z-score or max-min or None, defaults to z-score.

  • input_max_scale The scaling factor of the input time series to generate.

  • output_max_scale The scaling factor of the output time series to generate.

  • offset The offset mean and std for the input time series.

  • save_path The path to save the generated time series, defaults to None means not to save the data.

static save_s2data(symbol: str | Node | NodeList, excitation: ndarray, response: ndarray, save_path: str | None = None) → bool[source]#

Saves S2 data (symbolic expressions and time series) to the specified location.

This function works with load_s2data to provide a complete save/load workflow. Supports multiple file formats (.npy, .npz) and handles directory creation.

Parameters:

  • symbol Symbolic expression data generated by S2Generator (Node, NodeList, or str).

  • excitation Input excitation time series data.

  • response Response time series data obtained from the system.

  • save_path Save location with two input options: - Directory path: data will be saved as s2data.npz in this directory; - Full file path: must end with .npy or .npz extension.

Returns:

Boolean indicating success status of the save operation.

S2Generator.plot_symbol(symbol: str | Node | NodeList, width: int | None = 20, height: int | None = None, dpi: int | None = 160, return_all: str | None = False) → Figure | Tuple[Figure, Axes, List[Text]][source]#

This function visualizes symbolic data. Since the input symbolic expression data varies, you may need to adjust the width multiple times in actual use.

Parameters:

  • symbol The symbolic data to be visualized.

  • width The width of the drawn image may need to be adjusted multiple times.

  • height The height of the drawn image. If it is None, it will be automatically specified by the algorithm.

  • dpi The resolution of the visualization image.

  • return_all Whether to return all visualization information

Returns:

  • True: return (Figure, Axis, List[Text]),

  • False: return Figure.
